<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="S_Vector_FluxInt">
  <title>Flux Integrals</title>
<objectives>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        How can we measure how much of a vector field flows through a surface in space?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        How can we calculate the amount of a vector field that flows through common surfaces, such as the graph of a function <m>z=f(x,y)</m>?
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</objectives>
<subsection>
  <title>Introduction</title>
  <p>
    <xref ref="S-11-6-Parametric-Surfaces-Surface-Area"/> showed how we can use vector-valued functions of two variables to give a parameterization of a surface in space. For instance, the function <m>\vr(s,t)=\langle 2\cos(t)\sin(s), 2\sin(t)\sin(s),2\cos(s)\rangle</m> with domain <m>0\leq t\leq 2 \pi</m> and <m>0\leq s\leq \pi</m> parameterizes a sphere of radius <m>2</m> centered at the origin. <xref ref="S-11-6-Parametric-Surfaces-Surface-Area"/> also gives examples of how to write parameterizations based on other geometric relationships like when one coordinate can be written as a function of the other two. In <xref ref="SS-11-6-2-Surface-Area-Parametrically-Defined-Surfaces"/>, we set up a Riemann sum based on a parameterization that would measure the surface area of our curved surfaces in space.
  </p>
  <p>
    In <xref ref="fig_Vector_FluxInt_ParaPic"/>, we plot a surface using a parametrization <m>\vr(s,t)=\langle{f(s,t),g(s,t),h(s,t)}\rangle</m>. The magenta curves represent curves where <m>s</m> varies and <m>t</m> is held constant, while the yellow curves represent curves where <m>t</m> varies and <m>s</m> is held constant. The vector in magenta is
    <m>\vr_s=\frac{\partial \vr}{\partial s}=\langle{f_s,g_s,h_s}\rangle</m> which measures the direction and magnitude of change in the coordinates of the surface when only <m>s</m> is varied. Similarly, the vector in yellow is <m>\vr_t=\frac{\partial \vr}{\partial t}=\langle{f_t,g_t,h_t}\rangle</m> which measures the direction and magnitude of change in the coordinates of the surface when only <m>t</m> is varied. We also plot the parallelogram that is formed by <m>\vr_s</m> and <m>\vr_t</m>, which is tangent to the surface. The area of this parallelogram offers an approximation for the surface area of a patch of the surface.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_Vector_FluxInt_ParaPic">
    <caption>A three-dimensional plot of <xref ref="F_11_6_approx"/></caption>
    <interactive title="sage_para_pic" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1.10" label="int_Vector_FluxInt_ParaPic">
      <description><p>A three-dimensional plot of <xref ref="F_11_6_approx"/></p>
    </description><slate surface="sage">
        var('t,s,u,v,z,y,z')
        f=-x^2/2-3*y^3/3
        @interact
        def _(a=slider(-1,1,.5,0,label="s value"),b=slider(-1,1,.5,.5,label="t value")):
          plot1=plot3d(f,(x,-1,1),(y,-1,1),frame=False,opacity=.3)+sphere((a,b,f(x=a,y=b)),size=.05,color="black")
          for i in range(0,5):
            plot1+=parametric_plot3d((s,-1+i/2,f(x=s,y=-1+i/2)),(s,-1,1),color="#D81B60")
            plot1+=parametric_plot3d((-1+i/2,s,f(y=s,x=-1+i/2)),(s,-1,1),color="#FFC107")
          f_val=f(x=a,y=b)
          pos=(a,b,f_val)
          fx=diff(f,x)(x=a,y=b)
          fy=diff(f,y)(x=a,y=b)
          vt=(1/2+a,b,1/2*fx+f_val)
          vs=(a,b+1/2,1/2*fy+f_val)
          cr=(a-fx/2,b-fy/2,1/2+f_val)
          vectt=arrow3d(pos,vt,color="#D81B60")
          vects=arrow3d(pos,vs,color="#FFC107")
          plot1+=vectt+vects
          plot1+=parametric_plot3d((a+t/2,b+s/2,f_val+t/2*fx+s/2*fy),(t,0,1),(s,0,1),color="orange",opacity=.6)
          plot1+=arrow3d(pos,cr,color="#004D40")
          show(plot1)
      </slate>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

  <p>
    From <xref ref="S-Precalc-CrossProduct"/>, we also know that
    <m>\vr_s\times \vr_t</m> (plotted in green) will be orthogonal to both <m>\vr_s</m> and <m>\vr_t</m> and its magnitude will be given by the area of the parallelogram.
  </p>
  <worksheet>
  <exploration workspace="1.5in" xml:id="PA_Vector_FluxInt">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        In this preview activity, we will explore the parameterizations of a few familiar surfaces and confirm some of the geometric properties described in the introduction above.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task xml:id="task_PA_Vector_FluxInt_Param">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the ideas from <xref ref="S-11-6-Parametric-Surfaces-Surface-Area"/> to give a parameterization <m>\vr(s,t)</m> of the following surface. Be sure to specify the bounds on each of your parameters.
	      </p>
	      <p>
          <m>S_1</m>: the right circular cylinder centered on the <m>x</m>-axis of radius 2 when <m>0\leq x\leq 5</m>
        </p>
	    </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(s,t)=\langle s, 2\cos(t),2\sin(t) \rangle</m> for <m> t \in [0,2\pi], s \in [0,5]</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(s,t)=\langle s, 2\cos(t),2\sin(t) \rangle</m> for <m> t \in [0,2\pi], s \in [0,5]</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Draw a graph of <m>S_1</m> from the previous part. Label the points that correspond to <m>(s,t)</m> points of <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(0,1)</m>, <m>(1,0)</m>, and <m>(2,3)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      
      <solution>
        <p>
          The four points correspond to <m>(0,2,0)</m>, <m>(1,2,0)</m>, <m>(0,2\cos(1),0)</m>, and <m>(2,2\cos(3),2\sin(3))</m>. 
        </p>
        <interactive xml:id="exercise-testing9" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">

          <slate surface="sage">

<xi:include href="./interacts/demo.sage9.txt" parse="text"/>

</slate>

<description><p>ADD ALT TEXT TO THIS IMAGE</p></description></interactive>

<program>

<code>

<xi:include href="./interacts/demo.sage9.txt" parse="text"/>

</code>

</program>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task xml:id="task_PA_Vector_FluxInt_Tangents">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For the parameterization from <xref ref="task_PA_Vector_FluxInt_Param" text="local">part</xref>, calculate <m>\vr_s</m>, <m>\vr_t</m>, and <m>\vr_s \times \vr_t</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\vr_s \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t \amp = \langle 0,-2 \sin(t) , 2 \cos(t) \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t \amp = \langle 0,-2 \cos(t) , -2 \sin(t) \rangle </mrow>
          </md> 
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\vr_s \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t \amp = \langle 0,-2 \sin(t) , 2 \cos(t) \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t \amp = \langle 0,-2 \cos(t) , -2 \sin(t) \rangle </mrow>
          </md> 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task xml:id="task_PA_Vector_FluxInt_partd">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For the parameterization from <xref ref="task_PA_Vector_FluxInt_Param" text="local">part</xref>, find the value for <m>\vr_s</m>,<m>\vr_t</m>, and <m>\vr_s \times \vr_t</m> at the <m>(s,t)</m> points of <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(0,1)</m>, <m>(1,0)</m>, and <m>(2,3)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\vr_s (0,0) \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t (0,0) \amp = \langle 0,0 ,2 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t (0,0) \amp = \langle 0,-2 , 0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s (1,0) \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t (1,0) \amp = \langle 0,0,2 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t (1,0) \amp = \langle 0,-2  , 0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s (0,1) \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t (0,1) \amp = \langle 0,-2\sin(1) ,2\cos(1) \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t (0,1) \amp = \langle 0,-2\cos(1),-2\sin(1) \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s (2,3) \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t (2,3) \amp = \langle 0,-2\sin(3),2\cos(3) \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t (2,3) \amp = \langle 0,-2 \cos(3), -2\sin(3) \rangle </mrow>
          </md> 
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\vr_s (0,0) \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t (0,0) \amp = \langle 0,0 ,2 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t (0,0) \amp = \langle 0,-2 , 0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s (1,0) \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t (1,0) \amp = \langle 0,0,2 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t (1,0) \amp = \langle 0,-2  , 0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s (0,1) \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t (0,1) \amp = \langle 0,-2\sin(1) ,2\cos(1) \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t (0,1) \amp = \langle 0,-2\cos(1),-2\sin(1) \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s (2,3) \amp = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_t (2,3) \amp = \langle 0,-2\sin(3),2\cos(3) \rangle </mrow>
            <mrow>\vr_s \times \vr_t (2,3) \amp = \langle 0,-2 \cos(3), -2\sin(3) \rangle </mrow>
          </md> 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Draw your vector results from <xref ref="task_PA_Vector_FluxInt_partd" text="local"/> on your graph and confirm the geometric properties described in the introduction to this section. Namely, <m>\vr_s</m> and <m>\vr_t</m> should be tangent to the surface, while <m>\vr_s \times \vr_t</m> should be orthogonal to the surface (in addition to <m>\vr_s</m> and <m>\vr_t</m>).
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <interactive xml:id="exercise-testing10" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">

          <slate surface="sage">

